<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="1" to="2" step="1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="4" to="5" step="1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="0.2" to="0.4" step="0.1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="c" from="-1" to="1" step="2"/>
  
  <math name="m">($a+$b)/2</math>
  <function name="f">$c*$k*(x-$a)*(x-$b)</function>
  <mathList name="eqSols">$a $b</mathList>
  <mathList name="Int2">(-1,$a) ($b,7)</mathList>
  <mathList name="Int1">($a,$b)</mathList>
  
</setup>

<p>
  Consider an autonomous differential equation of the form 
  <me>
    \frac{dy}{dt} = f(y)
  </me>
  for which a plot of <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> as a function of <m>y</m> is given by the following graph.
</p>
    

<graph size="medium" xMin="-1" xMax="7" yMin="-4" yMax="4" showNavigation="false" fixAxes="true">
  $f
  <label anchor="(6.25,0.25)"><m>y</m></label>
  <label anchor="(0.4,3.5)"><m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m></label>
</graph>

<p>
  Use the graph to respond to the following questions.
</p>

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        Determine all equilibrium solutions of the differential equation <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = f(y)</m>.  If there is more than one, separate them with commas; if there are none, enter <q>none</q>.
      </p>
      <p>
        equilibrium solutions <m>y = </m><mathInput name="eqSolsEntered"/><answer unorderedCompare><award><when>$eqSolsEntered=$eqSols</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        For what intervals(s) of <m>y</m>-values for <m>-1 < y < 7</m> will the solution to the differential equation be an increasing function of <m>t</m>?  State your answer(s) in interval notation, separating more than one interval with commas.  For example, if you find that the solution function is increasing for <m>2< y < 4</m> and <m>5 < y < 6</m>, enter <q><m>(2,4),(5,6)</m></q>.  If there is no such interval, enter <q>none</q>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The solution increases on the <m>y</m>-interval(s) 
        <mathInput name="ans1"/>
        <answer unorderedCompare><award><when>
          ( $$f($m) > 0 and $ans1=$Int1 ) or ( 0 > $$f($m) and $ans1=$Int2 )
          </when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        For what intervals(s) of <m>y</m>-values for <m>-1 < y < 7</m> will the solution to the differential equation be a decreasing function of <m>t</m>?  State your answer(s) in interval notation, separating more than one interval with commas.  For example, if you find that the solution function is decreasing for <m>2< y < 4</m> and <m>5 < y < 6</m>, enter <q><m>(2,4),(5,6)</m></q>. If there is no such interval, enter <q>none</q>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The solution decreases on the <m>y</m>-interval(s) 
        <mathInput name="ans2"/>
        <answer unorderedCompare><award><when>
          ( $$f($m) > 0 and $ans2=$Int2 ) or ( 0 > $$f($m) and $ans2=$Int1 )
          </when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Finally, classify the stability of each of the equilibrium solutions.  The equilibrium solution <m>y = $a</m> is <choiceInput name="d1" inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>stable</choice>
          <choice>unstable</choice>
          <choice>semistable</choice>
        </choiceInput>, and the equilibrium solution <m>y = $b</m> is <choiceInput name="d2" inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>stable</choice>
          <choice>unstable</choice>
          <choice>semistable</choice>
        </choiceInput>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer><award><when>
          (($d1.selectedIndices=3 and $$f($m) > 0) and ($d2.selectedIndices=2 and $$f($m) > 0)) 
          or 
          (($d1.selectedIndices=2 and 0 > $$f($m)) and ($d2.selectedIndices=3 and 0 > $$f($m))) 
        </when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</p>
